CUI Reduction System - Reference
=================================

What it does
------------
Takes a large set of extracted CUIs per clinical phrase and reduces them to a concise, non-redundant set with confidence scores.


Pipeline (6 steps in order)
----------------------------
1. CUI Extraction - calls API, gets candidate CUIs with distances per phrase
2. SAB Filter - keeps only CUIs from allowed vocabs (ICD10CM, ICD10PCS, ICD9CM, SNOMEDCT_US, LNC)
3. Hierarchy Reduction - removes parent when more specific child exists (uses IC scores)
4. Embedding Reduction - removes true duplicates within semantic clusters
5. Cross-Topic Dedup - catches duplicates across different topics (only for >200 CUIs)
6. Confidence Scoring - ranks survivors by relevance


Confidence Score
----------------
Three signals, all [0,1]:
- Extraction Proximity: 1/(1+distance) — how close CUI was to the phrase in API
- Semantic Centrality: cosine(embedding, topic_centroid) — how central in its own topic
- Retention Power: log(1+absorbed)/log(1+max_absorbed) — how many duplicates it absorbed

Weights are automatic per phrase:
- Compute std of each signal across the phrase's CUIs
- weight = std / sum(stds)
- Signal that spreads more = more discriminating = more weight
- Flat signal = near-zero weight automatically
- If all flat, fallback to equal weights

Without extraction distances (patient documents): only centrality + retention used.

Centrality uses topic centroid (average of CUIs in same topic), not global centroid.


Duplicate Detection (5 checks, ALL must pass to remove)
--------------------------------------------------------
1. Close embedding distance (below Otsu threshold)
2. Overlapping semantic types (same UMLS semantic type group)
3. Not parent-child (both stay)
4. Overlapping ancestors (same branch in UMLS hierarchy)
5. Sibling guard — if both are leaf CUIs under the same parent, keep both
   (UMLS distinguished them for a reason, e.g. left knee vs right knee)

Any check fails = both CUIs kept.

No text or preferred terms used anywhere. All checks are purely structural
(embeddings, hierarchy graph, semantic types).


What you must provide before running
--------------------------------------
- UMLS hierarchy graph (networkx DiGraph, parent-child) — required, pipeline breaks without it
- IC precomputed dict {CUI: score} — optional, falls back to BFS from graph
- BigQuery tables (MRCONSO, MRSTY, embeddings) — required
- Extraction API endpoint — required


Pickle caches
-------------
- metadata_cache.pkl — CUI terms, semantic types, vocabs. If missing: queries BigQuery
- embedding_cache.pkl — CUI vectors. If missing: queries BigQuery
- extraction_cache.pkl — API results per phrase. If missing: calls API again

First run without pickles = slower (more BQ/API calls). Cached after that.

IC scores and ancestor lookups are in-memory only, no pickle. Recomputed each run.


Fast path vs full path
-----------------------
- 200 CUIs or fewer: fast path, direct pairwise dedup, skips components/Louvain
- More than 200: full path with graph components, Louvain clustering, cross-topic dedup


Output per phrase
-----------------
- Ranked CUI list with confidence scores
- Per-CUI: confidence, proximity, centrality, retention, semantic types, absorbed CUIs
- Topic clusters with member CUIs
- Full audit trail (every removal with reason)


Topic Generation (no ScaNN)
----------------------------
Topics are built using numpy cosine k-NN + Louvain. No ScaNN dependency.

1. Cosine similarity between all CUI embeddings (numpy dot product, vectors are L2-normalized)
2. Build weighted graph — edge if similarity above mean k-th neighbor distance
3. Louvain community detection — each community = one topic
4. Large topics (> sqrt(N)) get re-split at higher Louvain resolution
5. Singleton CUIs merge into nearest topic by centroid similarity

For >200 CUIs, graph components (Union-Find on shared UMLS ancestors) split CUIs first,
then Louvain runs within each component. This prevents unrelated CUIs from clustering together.
